      "role": "user",
      "content": "yea i get that. so if i add the shrinkage value to my COGS and subtract it from my ending inventory, how exactly does that change the final ratio? like, does the ratio go up or down when i include the lost stock? and do u have a specific formula for the 'adjusted' ratio?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "By adding the shrinkage to COGS and subtracting it from ending inventory, you are essentially making your numbers *worse* for the inventory turnover ratio, which is exactly what you want to show your boss! Because shrinkage is inventory that vanished without being sold, it makes your inventory look smaller than it truly is, and your sales (COGS) look bigger than they should be relative to what you actually moved.\n\nThe standard Inventory Turnover Ratio is:\n\n$$\\text{Inventory Turnover Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}$$\n\nWhen you adjust it, you are using an **Adjusted COGS** and an **Adjusted Average Inventory**.\n\n1.  **Adjusted COGS:** $\\text{Reported COGS} + \\text{Shrinkage Value}$\n2.  **Adjusted Ending Inventory:** $\\text{Reported Ending Inventory} - \\text{Shrinkage Value}$\n3.  **Adjusted Average Inventory:** $(\\text{Beginning Inventory} + \\text{Adjusted Ending Inventory}) / 2$\n\nSo, the **Adjusted Inventory Turnover Ratio** becomes:\n\n$$\\text{Adjusted Ratio} = \\frac{\\text",
